<section xml:id="sec-gensolns-initialvalues" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>General Solutions and Initial Value Problems</title>

<p>
  On the previous page, we found that one solution to <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 3P</m> is <m>P(t) = e^{3t}</m>. In fact, all possible solutions, called the <term>general solution</term>, are of the form <m>P(t) = Ce^{3t}</m>, where <m>C</m> is any real number. Can you see why this is always a solution? Give it a think before revealing below!
</p>

<solution>
  <title>Why is <m>P(t) = Ce^{3t}</m> always a solution?</title>
  <p>
    On the previous page we already showed that <m>e^{3t}</m> is a solution using the chain rule. It turns out the same argument works with any constant in front. Let's check with <m>C = 4</m> as an example:
    <me>\frac{d}{dt}(4e^{3t}) = 3 \cdot \underbrace{4e^{3t}}_{=\,P} = 3P. \checkmark</me>
    The constant <m>4</m> just comes along for the ride, it doesn't affect the chain rule calculation at all. So by the same reasoning, for any real number <m>C</m>:
    <me>\frac{d}{dt}(Ce^{3t}) = 3\underbrace{Ce^{3t}}_{=\,P} = 3P. \checkmark</me>
    Therefore <m>P(t) = Ce^{3t}</m> is a solution for any real number <m>C</m>.
  </p>
</solution>
<p>
  We will justify why this captures <em>all</em> solutions later when we study separable ODEs. For now, this idea generalizes naturally to the family of ODEs <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = kP</m>.
</p>

<observation xml:id="obs-general-solution-population">
  <title>Solution to the Population Growth Model</title>
  <p>
    A simple model of a population <m>P(t)</m> is that the rate of change is proportional to the population. So <m>P(t)</m> satisfies:
    <me>\frac{dP}{dt} = kP.</me>
    The <term>general solution</term> to this differential equation is:
    <me>P(t) = Ce^{kt},</me>
    where varying over any real number for <m>C</m> gives all possible solutions.
  </p>
</observation>

<exercise xml:id="ex-mc-general-soln-population">
  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the general solution to <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 2P</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>
  <choices randomize="no">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>P(t) = Ce^{2t}</m>, where <m>C</m> is any real number.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Correct! This matches the general solution <m>P(t) = Ce^{kt}</m> with <m>k = 2</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>P(t) = Ce^{t}</m>, where <m>C</m> is any real number.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Not quite — check the exponent. The ODE is <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 2P</m>, so <m>k = 2</m>, giving <m>e^{2t}</m> not <m>e^t</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>P(t) = 2e^{t}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Not quite — this is a specific solution, not the general one. The general solution has an arbitrary constant <m>C</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>P(t) = Ce^{2}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Not quite — the <m>t</m> belongs in the exponent! The general solution is <m>P(t) = Ce^{2t}</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
</exercise>



<p>
  In the general solution <m>P(t) = Ce^{2t}</m>, each value of <m>C</m> gives a different <term>specific solution</term> — together they form a whole family of curves. For instance:
</p>

<md>
  <mrow>C = 2: \amp\quad P(t) = 2e^{2t}</mrow>
  <mrow>C = -1: \amp\quad P(t) = -e^{2t}</mrow>
  <mrow>C = 0: \amp\quad P(t) = 0e^{2t} = 0</mrow>
</md>

<p>
  Use the slider below to explore how the value of <m>C</m> affects the solution curve.
</p>

<figure xml:id="fig-population-slider">
  <caption>Solutions <m>P(t) = Ce^{2t}</m> for varying values of <m>C</m>.</caption>
  <interactive xml:id="interactive-population-slider" iframe="interactive-population-slider.html" width="80%" aspect="3:2">
    <static>
      <p>
        An interactive graph showing the solution curve <m>P(t) = Ce^{2t}</m> with a slider to vary <m>C</m> from <m>-5</m> to <m>5</m>. As <m>C</m> increases the curve grows more steeply, and when <m>C = 0</m> the solution is the equilibrium <m>P(t) = 0</m>.
      </p>
    </static>
  </interactive>
</figure>

<p>
  Notice how the red dot representing <m>P(0)</m> moves as you vary <m>C</m>. This is no coincidence: since <m>P(0) = Ce^{2 \cdot 0} = C</m>, the initial value of the population is exactly <m>C</m>. Specifying an <term>initial condition</term> like <m>P(0) = 200</m> pins down exactly which curve we are on, giving us a <term>specific solution</term>.
</p>

<definition xml:id="def-initial-value-problem">
  <title>Initial Value Problem</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      An <term>initial value problem (IVP)</term> consists of a differential equation together with one or more initial conditions. The goal is to find a <term>specific solution</term> that satisfies both the ODE and the initial condition(s).
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<p>
  Now we will get some practice finding a specific solution to an initial value problem!
</p>
<example xml:id="ex-initial-condition">
  <title>Applying an Initial Condition</title>
  <p>
    We have seen that the general solution to <m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 2P</m> is <m>P(t) = Ce^{2t}</m>. What is the specific solution such that the initial population at <m>t = 0</m> is <m>P(0) = 200</m>?
  </p>
  <hint>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>For <m>P(0) = 200</m>, substitute <m>0</m> wherever you see <m>t</m> and <m>200</m> wherever you see <m>P(t)</m> in <m>P(t) = Ce^{2t}</m>. Then solve for <m>C</m>.</li>
        <li>You will need to use the fact that <m>e^0 = 1</m>.</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </hint>
  <solution>
    <p>
      We substitute <m>P(0) = 200</m> into the general solution:
      <md>
        <mrow>P(t) \amp= Ce^{2t}</mrow>
        <mrow>200 \amp= Ce^{2 \cdot 0}</mrow>
        <mrow>200 \amp= Ce^{0}</mrow>
        <mrow>200 \amp= C.</mrow>
      </md>
      So <m>C = 200</m>, and the specific solution is:
      <me>P(t) = 200e^{2t}.</me>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

